# CPOM Compliance Structure

Builds a jurisdiction-specific compliance structure for CPOM restrictions and physician independence.

## Prerequisites

1. Jurisdictions of operation and licensure footprints
2. Services and modalities (in-person, telemedicine, dental, optometry, PT, etc.)
3. Ownership and capitalization plan, including non-physician investors
4. Proposed operating model (PC/PA, MSO, PPM, hospital-employed)
5. Current contracts (MSA, equity, leases, IP, branding, financing)
6. Referral relationships, payer mix, and compensation models
7. Affiliate entities and shared services org chart
8. Compliance history or known issues

## Output Structure / Process

Use the following outline and fill each section with jurisdiction-specific detail.

```markdown
1. Executive Summary
2. CPOM Doctrine Overview (purpose, scope, enforcement posture)
3. Jurisdiction Matrix (state-by-state)
4. Structure Selection and Rationale
5. Governance and Ownership Controls
6. MSA Architecture and Key Clauses
7. Operational Compliance Controls
8. Training, Monitoring, and Reporting
9. Risk Assessment and Mitigation
10. Approvals, Effective Date, Review Cadence
```

### Jurisdiction Matrix (required)

| State | CPOM Status (Prohibited / Limited / None) | Licensed Entity Type | Ownership/Control Limits | Medical Director Requirements | Key Authority | Enforcement Notes | Sector Carveouts | Notes |
|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|
| [State] | [Status] | [PC/PA/etc.] | [%/board control] | [Y/N + details] | [Statute/reg/case] [VERIFY] | [Board activity] | [Dental/optometry/PT] | [Local counsel flags] |

### Structure Options (select and justify)

| Model | When Used | Ownership/Control | Core Legal Risk | Mitigations |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| Physician-owned PC/PA + MSO | CPOM-restricted states | Physicians own and control practice | De facto control by MSO | Governance + MSA guardrails |
| PPM with long-term MSO | Multi-state rollups | Split control | Fee-splitting, AKS, Stark | FMV, independence, audits |
| Hospital-employed model | Integrated systems | Hospital entity | Employment restrictions | Board approvals, contracts |
| Friendly PC | High-risk, investor-led | Non-physician influence | Regulatory recharacterization | Avoid or restructure |

### Governance and Ownership Controls

Checklist of non-delegable physician controls:

- Clinical decision-making and protocols
- Physician hiring, credentialing, and termination
- Fee-setting and coding policies
- Patient acceptance, referrals, discharge
- Quality assurance and peer review
- Ownership transfers of the professional entity

### MSA Architecture (required clauses)

| Clause | Required Language | Red Flags | Evidence to Keep |
|---|---|---|---|
| Scope of Services | Admin only, no clinical control | MSO controls care | Service catalog, SOPs |
| Physician Independence | Physician entity retains final authority | MSO approval rights | Board minutes |
| Compensation | FMV, no volume/value | Percentage of revenue tied to referrals | FMV study [VERIFY] |
| Term/Exit | Physician ability to exit without patient loss | Non-compete blocking patient continuity | Transition plan |
| IP/Branding | Practice controls clinical brand use | MSO owns clinical identity | Licenses and consents |
| Compliance | Mutual CPOM compliance, audit rights | One-way enforcement | Audit reports |

### Operational Compliance Controls (assign owners and cadence)

| Control Point | Owner | Evidence | Cadence |
|---|---|---|---|
| Physician hiring approvals | Medical director | Approval log | Per hire |
| Fee-setting process | Physician board | Pricing minutes | Annual/PRN |
| Clinical protocols | Physician committee | Protocol approvals | Semiannual |
| Marketing review | Compliance + physician | Ad approvals | Per campaign |
| Equipment purchases impacting care | Physician sign-off | Capital approvals | Per purchase |
| MSA performance | Compliance | SLA and audit file | Quarterly |

### Training and Monitoring

- Onboarding training for physicians, admins, executives
- Annual CPOM refreshers with attestation
- Quarterly MSA compliance audits
- Whistleblower reporting path and non-retaliation policy

### Risk Assessment and Mitigation

| Risk | Consequences | Mitigation |
|---|---|---|
| CPOM violation | License discipline, voided contracts | Restructure governance, legal opinion |
| AKS exposure | Civil/criminal penalties | FMV, commercial reasonableness [VERIFY] |
| Stark exposure | Payment denials, refunds | Exception mapping [VERIFY] |
| False Claims | Qui tam exposure | Compliance audits, disclosures |
| Reputational harm | Recruiting/payer impact | Documentation, remediation |

## Guidelines

- Verify each jurisdiction with current statutes, regs, and medical board guidance; mark uncertain cites as `[VERIFY]`.
- Do not assume CPOM is absent in states with weak enforcement; document enforcement posture separately.
- Keep physician-owned entity assets and bank accounts separate from the MSO.
- Avoid MSA terms that give the MSO veto power over clinical or physician personnel decisions.
- Ensure compensation is FMV and not tied to referrals or clinical volume; document methodology.
- If using friendly PC arrangements, require enhanced independence safeguards or avoid entirely.

## Key Citations to Confirm

- Anti-Kickback Statute, 42 U.S.C. § 1320a-7b(b) [VERIFY]
- Stark Law, 42 U.S.C. § 1395nn [VERIFY]
- OIG compliance program guidance (provider-specific) [VERIFY]

## Approval and Review

- Effective date, signatories (MSO, physician entity, counsel)
- Review cadence: annual and upon material operational changes
